bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: In December 1972, a program committee of Trustees of the Rockefeller Foundation (RF) was appointed to conduct a formal review of the overall programs and policies of the RF since 1958. One result of this review was the establishment in 1973 of a new program titled Conflict in International Relations (CIR), under the guidance of Elmore Jackson and Joseph E. Black, Director for Social Sciences. The program, under the Division of Social Sciences, was to be "directed toward the support of measures for the anticipation, avoidance, and resolution of conflicts that are likely to disrupt the international community, and the development of international institutions with greater capacity for dealing effectively with emerging issues of global interdependency." (RF Annual Report, 1973, p. 10)

During its first 18 months, emphasis was placed on analyzing several of the basic emerging issues in the international community – including the economic and security implications of scarce resources, the impact of population growth, low food reserves, possible climate change, and the escalation of military budgets in response to the increased costs of ever more sophisticated military equipment (E. Jackson to J. Leonard, January 24, 1975) – and in holding discussions with research and foundation executives in the United States and overseas. Building on this analysis and these discussions, the CIR program in 1975 began to devote more attention both to the means through which international institutions capable of handling these issues could be developed and to the development of leadership through its fellowships.

In its early years, CIR's areas of focus included: International economic and resource issues; arms control and international security; new approaches to world order; and analysis of particular conflicts. The emphasis was on the anticipation, control, and resolution of conflict. Grants were given to institutions, awards made to outstanding persons in the field of international relations, and conferences were sponsored.

In 1976, the RF Trustees authorized a new Division of International Relations with Mason Willrich as its Director, and in 1977, following a major review of the CIR program, a revised program – titled International Relations (IR) – was approved and launched under the Division of International Relations.

The new IR program was to focus on three areas: World energy; world food and agriculture; and regional conflicts and security arrangements. Further adjustments to the program were made in 1978, with areas of focus defined as: World energy; international economic policy; and regional conflicts and security arrangements.

Within each of these areas, the primary objectives were: "(1) to identify core problems for which cooperative action is or will be required for effective management, or for the avoidance or resolution of major conflict; (2) to assess such problems from a global perspective and in context in order to develop and evaluate alternative courses of action for coping with them; (3) to encourage development of scholarly and professional competence in policy analysis; and (4) to increase public understanding of the issues and alternatives and the need for timely action." (RF Annual Report, 1979, p. 81)

Through its IR program, RF supported efforts "to promote international collaboration in pursuit of long-term common national interests; that stress the need for practical solutions that can command wide public support rather than theoretical grand designs; that bring a variety of disciplines to bear on issues; and that address problems in a multidisciplinary fashion." (RF Annual Report, 1980, p. 66)

In December 1981, the RF revised its guidelines for the IR program. The component on world energy problems was phased out. The program, beginning in 1982, would make grants that supported independent research and policy analysis of the long-range interests that governments have in international security and economic cooperation. Aware that peaceful relations among nations was a vital corollary to the objectives of its grantmaking efforts, the RF set the following goals for the IR program, as outlined in the Foundation's 1982 Annual Report (p. 65):
1. Within the United States, to strengthen the contribution of nongovernmental international relations research to U. S. foreign policy;

2. In countries other than the United States, to strengthen the analytical capacity of international relations research institutions that can operate substantially without government constraint and have the potential to increase the intellectual underpinnings of these countries' foreign policies;
3. To provide more effective opportunities for public and private experts from different countries to analyze problems jointly and develop practical solutions that can command wide public support;
4. Through its fellowship program and other mechanisms, to identify outstanding young people trained in international relations and increase their opportunities for career development.

Over the next few years, the IR program continued its emphasis on international security and economic cooperation, providing funding to strengthen the contribution of independent research and policy analysis to the articulation of the long-range interests facing governments in these areas. In 1983, the Foundation made several experimental grants to encourage American women leaders to engage in the debate over U. S. national security policy. In 1984, final support was provided to the Group of Thirty, a nonprofit consultative group initiated by the RF in 1978 – and officially titled "Consultative Group on International Economic and Monetary Affairs" – to deal with international economic and monetary problems.

In 1986, the decision was made to close the International Relations division of the RF, a decision based both on the need to concentrate time and resources on the RF's new directions in developing-country programs and on evidence of substantially increased contribution by other foundations to the international relations field, especially in the area of arms control. (Summary of Minutes, RF Board of Trustees Meeting, June 20, 1986) A number of the program interests of the IR division relating to international development were incorporated in the RF's new International Program to Support Science-Based Development. In all instances, grant commitments made prior to the decision to close were not affected. The IR program was formally terminated on December 31, 1986.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The bulk of this series is correspondence. Records also include minutes, evaluations, and supplementary material of a general nature about the Conflict in International Relations/International Relations program, as well as documentation of grants awarded and fellowship files. Many of the grant and fellowship files are enriched by supplementary material, which may be in the form of publications, papers, reports, agendas or minutes of conferences, books, or other printed material. The supplementary material often contains the fruit that has resulted from a grant or fellowship.

The material in this series primarily covers the period from 1972/73 - when the Conflict in International Relations program was first established - through 1986, when its successor, the International Relations program, was terminated. Earliest dated material, however, dates from 1960 and latest is from 1994.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Series 155 contains one subseries - Subseries 155E: International Relations - Fellowships.

The arrangement reflects the filing system used by the Foundation, with minutes, correspondence and general information placed at the beginning of the series followed by material on grantee institutions, arranged alphabetically. Files are arranged in chronological order. Within each folder, material is arranged in chronological order for the first half of the collection and in reverse chronological order for the last half of the collection.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Standard processing conducted by Gail Antos, 2016. All records have been placed in acid free lignin free folders and rehoused in archival manuscript boxes. Original file titles have been primarily maintained.
